uits adapt, redefine, cope with, and make sense of the positive and negative aspects of their training and apprenticeship. Bringing together rigorous quantitative analyses with rich ethnographic description, Fair Cop provides new empirical data and theoretical understanding about the reproduction and change of police culture.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aPolice training. 0aPolicexAttitudes. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Sociology / General.2bisacsh1 aChan, Janet, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDevery, Chris, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDevery, Christopher, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aDoran, Sally, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aDoran, Sally, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Toronto Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311049095440uhttps://doi.org/10.3138/978144267478340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781442674783423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781442674783.jpg  a978-3-11-049095-4  University of Toronto Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aEBA_STMALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA12STME  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK